<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Middle-earth vs. Lord of the Rings<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.76)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11912'>Josh "Aragorn_1379" Evans</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=11912&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 9, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Obviously we all know about Decipher&#39;s Lord of the Rings TCG.  But who remembers Iron Crown Enterprise&#39;s Middle-earth CCG?  I played both and enjoy both, so I thought I&#39;d do a compare and contrast on some of the differences between the game.<br>
<br>
Simplicity.<br>
<br>
Lord of the Rings wins hands down.  Anyone who ever picked up a MECCG rules booklet probably spent some time scratching their head; just when you thought you had the game figured out, there were 2 more levels of rules to look at.  Things like General Influence, Direct Influence, influence checks, etc. sometimes make MECCG too complicated to be fun.  LoTR is much much simpler, and that can make for funner games; but the complexity of the rules can make for huge variety of strategies for MECCG, meaning the game takes a LOT longer to get old.<br>
<br>
Available cards for Hazards/Shadow.<br>
<br>
MECCG cleans up obviously; but it&#39;s really not fair to compare a new game with only 3 sets out to a mature game that had 6 sets that I can recall immediately (there may be more).  However, even looking at just the first set for each (FOTR for LOTR and Middle-earth: The Wizards for MECCG), MECCG had many more choices; dragons (my personal favorite), Nazgul, orcs, corruption, undead, animals, many more.  LOTR so far has Nazgul, Uruk-hai, Orcs, and Sauron Orcs; we also know the Raiders are going to be in The Two Towers.  MECCG also gave the player the ability to play as a Ringwraith, the Balrog, or a Fallen-wizard instead of as one of the Five Wizards (Gandalf, Saruman, Alatar, Pallando, and Radagast) for those of you who just looove being the bad guy :D.<br>
<br>
Available cards for Resources/Free Peoples.<br>
<br>
Again, MECCG has many many more choices.  You can find the One Ring and take it to Mount Doom.  You can gather the support of the Factions of the Free Peoples of Middle-earth in your war against Sauron.  You can gather important items that will inspire the Free Peoples.  And of course there&#39;s many mini-quests: reforging the broken shards of Narsil into Aragorn&#39;s sword Anduril (probably the thing I miss most in the LOTR movie and TCG).  Taking Thorin&#39;s group of Dwarves to the Lonely Mountain so he can become King under the Mountain.  LoTR we have only Gandalf beatdown, Gondor beatdown, denial, Elven archery, and Hobbit stealth.  There will be more I realize, with Rohan, the Ents, Frodo getting closer to Mordor, Pippin in Minas Tirith for the war in ROTK, GANDALF THE WHITE (I hope), etc.  But still I really doubt that LoTR will ever catch up to MECCG in this area.<br>
<br>
Gameplay.<br>
<br>
Which is funner?  That is subjective; I like Lord of the Rings, but I wish some elements from MECCG were in LOTR (corruption for others besides the Ring-bearer is one of my favorites).  But LOTR has lots of positives too.  I absolutely LOVE LOTR&#39;s archery.  Legolas in MECCG was useless, just a weak character; in LOTR he&#39;s just behind Gandalf and Aragorn in usefulness, sometimes ahead of them.  MECCG allowed you to roam Middle-earth at will, and this was fun; but the LOTR TCG&#39;s 9 sites are fun as well.  This is personal preference again.  My choice would be MECCG&#39;s system.  <br>
<br>
Accuracy concerning the works of J.R.R. Tolkien.<br>
<br>
Middle-earth cleans house.  Those cards are taken straight from the books, use art done by many, many artists so you get different impressions of what things looked like, and took their lore right out of the pages of the books.  LOTR is based on the movie, and has the movie&#39;s inaccuracies, such as Arwen leaving Rivendell to look for Frodo instead of Glorfindel, Aragorn refusing to take up the crown instead of being eager to do it (this leads to the absence of Anduril), the total absence of Tom Bombadil (no huge loss in my mind, but thats me) and the Barrow-downs (gahh one of the best scenes in the books), the inflation of Saruman&#39;s role, and so on (I need to stop now; I&#39;m a purist and each inaccuracy really gets under my skin, that is not the subject of this article).<br>
<br>
So which is better?  That depends solely on the player.  If you want simple, quick games, LOTR TCG is the one for you.  If you enjoy incredibly complex, confusing rules and STRATEGIES(something every LOTR player sometimes wishes more for), then MECCG is your game.  <br>
<br>
Have fun no matter where you roam in the world of J.R.R. Tolkien&#39;s Middle-earth (and it&#39;s card games).<br>
